###### 
*If you received this letter without images, or with a scam alert, that was because I imported the images in a way some email clients don't like. Hopefully this version will fix that.*





 There is no real world anymore.
 







 Rather, there is no difference between online and off, the real and the cyber. The borders of meatspace have dissolved in the caustic soup of bots, memes and cognitive hacks we call "the Discourse."
 







 ICYMI this week: The richest billionaire got hacked by a different billionaire, who sent him threatening memes and stole his dick pics. Allegedly.
 







 Jeff Bezos, a.k.a. Short Lex Luthor, opened a video file sent to him by Mohammed bin Salman, crown prince of Saudi Arabia. That file contained an exploit that allowed the Saudis to exfiltrate data from Bezos' phone, according to the report published by
 [Motherboard](https://www.vice.com/amp/en_us/article/v74v34/saudi-arabia-hacked-jeff-bezos-phone-technical-report?__twitter_impression=true) 
 . The prince later sent him a meme featuring a woman who resembled Bezos's mistress, Lauren Sanchez. At the time their relationship was not public. It's possible that this is how the National Enquirer acquired the compromising selfies with which they tried to blackmail Bezos in 2019.
 







 Opinions differ on whether the hack was connected to the extortion campaign. Which failed anyway, as Bezos called their bluff (in a post called "
 [No thank you, Mr. Pecker](https://medium.com/@jeffreypbezos/no-thank-you-mr-pecker-146e3922310f) 
 ," which incidentally is how any normal person would respond to a dick pic from Jeff Bezos).
 







 Some security experts have
 [questioned](https://mobile.twitter.com/thegrugq/status/1220160721838731264) 
 whether the forensic report is even accurate. Regardless, billionaires texting each other viruses on encrypted messenger is absolute cyberpunk gold. The 2020s were a long time coming, but they certainly made an entrance.
 







 I don't have any billionaires in my contacts. But I do bridge different communities: tech criticism, transhumanists, anticapitalist shitposters and general Weirdos. At least, that's what I found from analyzing my friends-of-friends network:
 







![the social graph is shaped like a fish with a red face, a blue underbelly, a yellow dorsal fin and a long green tail](data:image/png;base64,)








 This little fishy is a map of the accounts I follow on twitter as
 [@deepfates](https://twitter.com/deepfates) 
 . Most people, myself included, start a Twitter account and immediately follow anyone that seems the slightest bit interesting. This leads to a firehose of bullshit that makes the site unusable. Now I try to only follow the people whose posts I truly enjoy. I use lists and alt accounts to follow people who I only want to see at certain times.
 







 Don't squint: you don't have to read the map to make sense of it.
 







 Each dot is a Twitter account, each line is a connection between accounts (following, followed by, or mutually following). Accounts are positioned by the amount of connections between them, creating a social topology. This is a 2-dimensional physicalization of a high-dimensional space: each person may be said to be closer or farther from each other person in the graph.The algorithm that lays them out (ForceAtlas2) simulates attraction and repulsion until the nodes find equilibrium.
 







 The colors represent sub-communities, whose members are more closely connected to each other than to other parts of the graph. This is called the "modularity." I don't totally understand it, I just learned how to do this last week (from
 [this thread by @MenanderSoter](https://twitter.com/MenanderSoter/status/1219776869018587136) 
 ).
 







 The dots are sized by "in-degree": how many people on the map follow them. People with high in-degree are considered to be "authorities," whereas people with a high out-degree are "hubs". Because this is a graph of the people I like to follow, that means authorities are highly respected by the people I respect, and hubs respect a lot of the same people I respect. The biggest authority in the graph is William Gibson (@GreatDismal), which makes sense.
 







 This is the same map, but with nodes sized by out-degree:
 








![the social graph is shaped like a fish with a red face, a blue underbelly, a yellow dorsal fin and a long green tail](data:image/png;base64,)













 The out-degree map shows which accounts are hubs of my corner of the Twitterverse, who synthesize information from many sectors. Indeed, if m1k3y or enkiv2 or arikia link to something, I'm likely to read (or have already read) it. We pay attention to similar things, though we reside in different places.
 







 And the big green dot? That's my alt account,
 [@cat\_upgrades](https://app.tinyletter.com/twitter.com/cat_upgrades) 
 . I follow a lot of the same people with both accounts, but the alt is not quite centered on the graph. It's off in the green community, which consists of leftist shitposters (close to the main blob) and pure comedy accounts (the blob off to the right). This is an interesting group, because the comedy accounts don't interact with any of the other communities and form a sub-clique attached only to other comedians. The rationalist/insight-porn community, in yellow, is, similarly smeared but has a more even distribution.
 







 The red and blue communities are tightly linked. The blue one contains more people who I think of as "journalists" and the red more "sci-fi writers," although there's a lot of overlap between the two jobs these days. Blue also seems to have a lot of NYC-based people. Real-world proximity bleeding back into the digital space.
 







 Because there is no real world anymore. My internet friends live in a different world from my neighbors, and the intersection of those worlds makes a holographic reality just for me. We shape our online selves, and in turn they shape our lives.
 







 There was an interesting read at Ribbonfarm this week:
 [Being Your Selves: Identity R&D on alt Twitter, by Aaron Z. Lewis](https://www.ribbonfarm.com/2020/01/23/being-your-selves-identity-rd-on-alt-twitter/) 
 . It's long, but boils down to: having just one identity online sucks, because you get trapped in playing the part of Firstname Lastname rather than exploring different sides of yourself in different contexts. This is true, but shortsighted.
 







 The self is multiplicity. It's not a singular soul dancing through life in a series of masks. The self only exists as interaction. There is no person behind the mask. The self is a seething mass of urges and moods that change and are changed by the world and time.
 

 The self is a community of its own.
 





 It's cool to have alts, but that doesn't mean that you have a main. All online identities are already alts, and in-person identities are as well. The person you are in front of your mom, or your mistress, or the crown prince of Saudi Arabia: all different. Different but not separate. You morph. Your way of speaking, mannerisms, even your priorities will change based on the environment.
 







 And the environment will change you back. And your desire will change the environment again, in a feedback loop. Be careful who your friends are. If you're going to text with billionaires, do it on a burner phone.
 









 Thanks for reading,
 







 -- Max
